Research Goal

This research use the daily Apple and its supplers stock prices of the last 10 years starting from 2008 (Where Apple stock starts to skyrocket)

Suppliers Description
MU Major RAM supplier
JBL Major Phone Casings
ADI Touch screen controllers Provider
GLUU Major provider of iOS apps and mobile games
QCOM Supply Majority electronic components
STM Three-axis gyroscope and accelerometer
TXN Chip and control device

The table above shows the 7 major publically traded suppliers of Apple. The goal of this research is to:

  1. investigate whether stock of the suppliers of Apple explain apple stock price.

  2. I will run the regression of Apple stock price with its suppliers stock price specifically to determine who has the strongest correlation. After that I will also test the causal effect, and determine which specific stocks price change is causing most change of Apple stock.

  3. Finally I will find the combo of suppliers stock that mostly explain Apple Stock price; This research could be used as a hedging strategy to hedge risk of Apple stock price fluctuation, and therefore making Apple stock as a source of Dividend generation only security.

Data sourced from FactSet, a reliable financial database

From all the simple regression analysis above, we can conclude that AAPL is most correlated with TXN, ADI (High R square value and small residual standard error/ least correlated with QCOM, GLUU, and STM.

Multiple Regression to Determine the Optimum Group of Stocks

To find the best group of suppliers stocks that explain Apple stock price well, I need to start by incorporate every variables as they are all supplier of Apple:

\[ AAPL = \beta_0 + \beta_1MU + \beta_2ADI + \beta_3GLUU + \beta_4JBL + \beta_5QCOM + \beta_6STM + \beta_7TXN \]

Then from the simple regression before, I find Apple stock is not very correlated with QCOM, GLUU, and STM, so I will pick them out:

\[ AAPL = \beta_0 + \beta_1MU + \beta_2ADI + \beta_3JBL + \beta_4TXN \]

Then I will also run apple stock with only the two most correlated suppliers, TXN and ADI:

\[ AAPL = \beta_0 + \beta_1ADI + \beta_2TXN \]

AAPL.1 <- lm(AAPL ~ MU + ADI + GLUU + JBL + QCOM + STM + TXN, data=AAPLSTOCK) #Run a regression of all suppliers' stock
AAPL.2 <- lm(AAPL ~ MU + ADI + JBL + TXN, data=AAPLSTOCK) #Run a Regression excluding less correlated stocks
AAPL.3 <- lm(AAPL ~ ADI + TXN, data=AAPLSTOCK)#Run a regression with only most correlated stocks

This shows high signiciance to our model, and Apple stock is affected by all of its suppliers.

t-test and F-test

After determining the best model we are going to use (Which is include all the supplier stocks into Apple), we are going to use t-test and F-test to test specifically if the model explain Apples stock at all

t-test

The Hypothesis will be like this: \[ H_0: \beta_j = 0 \]

\[ H_1: \beta_j \neq 0 \] The point here is, We want to test if each specific variable in the model is meaningful at explaining Apple Stock.

sumres <- summary(AAPL.1) #assign summary of regression to an object
regtable <- sumres$coefficients #extract only Coefficient term from the summary table
bhat <- regtable[,1] #estimated value of each coefficient
se  <- regtable[,2] #standard error of each coefficient

( tstat <- (bhat - 0) / se ) #t-test
## (Intercept)          MU         ADI        GLUU         JBL        QCOM 
##   -4.577048    8.437873   13.593864   33.837728   14.288930  -14.082475 
##         STM         TXN 
##  -25.575840   18.483260
round((pval <- 2*pt(-abs(tstat),2539)), 5) #t-test's p-value
## (Intercept)          MU         ADI        GLUU         JBL        QCOM 
##           0           0           0           0           0           0 
##         STM         TXN 
##           0           0

From the result, we can see that the pvalues of all the explanatory variables are close to 0, which indicates that each variable in the model is meaningful at explaining Apple Stock.

F-test

The hypothesis here is: \[F={{\frac{SSR_{r}-SSR_{ur}}{SSR_{ur}}}\cdot{\frac{n-k-1}{q}}}= {{\frac{R^2_{ur}-R^2_{r}}{1-R^2_{ur}}}\cdot{\frac{n-k-1}{q}}}\] where q is the number of restrictions, n the number of observations and k the number of parameters in the regression.

The test is aiming to determine if the model is explaining Apple stock price at all. We will do one test that determine whether a restricted model without three least correlated stocks (QCOM / GLUU / STM) will be different from the unrestricted model. The hypothesis is below:

\[ H_0: \beta_3 = \beta_5 = \beta_6 = 0\] \[ H_1: at\,least\,one\,is\,different\,from\,0 \]

res.ur <- lm(AAPL ~ MU + ADI + GLUU + JBL + QCOM + STM + TXN, data=AAPLSTOCK) #unrestricted Regression
res.r <- lm(AAPL ~ MU + ADI + JBL + TXN, data=AAPLSTOCK) #Restricted Regression
( r2.ur <- summary(res.ur)$r.squared ) # R squared unrestricted
## [1] 0.9609522
( r2.r <- summary(res.r)$r.squared ) # R squared restricted 
## [1] 0.9251895
( F <- (r2.ur-r2.r) / (1-r2.ur) * 2539/3) #F-test
## [1] 775.1308
round(1-pf(F, 3,2539),5) #P-Value
## [1] 0

The result shows a p-value that is very close to 0, and therefore we should reject null hypothesis even at 99% confidence inteval and conclude that at least one beta of STM / GLUU / QCOM is meaningful to explain the Apple stock price.

From t-test and F-test, it is sufficient that under 99% confidence inteval that the model with all suppliers stock is sufficient to explain Apples stock price.

Prediction and Conclusion

After obtaining the best model, we want to do a prediction to see how our predicted stock price compare to the actual price. We will do this through making a point plot

Hedging Portfolio Performance

AAPLhat <- predict(lm(AAPL ~ MU + ADI + GLUU + JBL + QCOM + STM + TXN, data=AAPLSTOCK))
AAPLhatdataframe <- data.frame(AAPLhat) #transfer vector to dataframe
AAPLhatdataframe$Date = AAPLSTOCK$Date #Match the date column from Original dataframe to predicted dataframe
ggplot()+ 
geom_line(data=AAPLSTOCK, aes(x=Date,y=AAPL),color="Blue") +
geom_line(data=AAPLhatdataframe, aes(x=Date, y=AAPLhat), color="Red")+
labs(title="AAPL(Blue) and AAPLhat(Red)", y="AAPL and AAPLhat", x="Date") #Plot a line plot of apple stock and estimated stock price

Hedging Outcome

We are going to construct a portfolio consists of a long position in Apple stock and a short position of a portfolio of its suppliers stocks assigning weights according to their corresponding regression coefficent. We are going to backtest this strategys outcome by simply subtract the predicted value of apple stock from apple actual past stock price. If the hedge is successful, we are able to achieve $0 outcome, and very close to 0 standard deviation.

AAPLhatdataframe$Hedge = AAPLSTOCK$AAPL-AAPLhatdataframe$AAPLhat #Construct a hedge column that is the hedge result
summary(AAPLhatdataframe) #summarize the outcome

As we see, the hedge is not perfect, but control the portfolio outcome in the last 10 year to have a mean of 0, and an Standard deviation of 10.

That marks our conclusion of the research. We conclude that all the suppliers stocks reasonally explain apple stock price change. However, there are two main limitation: 1.Chance of reverse causation, meaning that it might be Apples extraordinary performance that affect all the other suppliers stock. 2.The hedge portfolio consists of all Apple suppliers Stock still cannot fully hedge the price change of Apple. There is tail risk of losing $25 still.
